"Powers L.A., Johnson T.C., Werne J.P., Castañeda I.S., Hopmans E.C., Sinninghe Damsté J.S., Schouten S.","Large temperature variability in the southern African tropics since the Last Glacial Maximum",2005,"Geophysical Research Letters","32","8",,"1","4",,,10.1029/2004GL022014,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-22944432536&partnerID=40&md5=08eef70a165cc3d2942f9cf97f78c7f6","Large Lakes Observatory, University of Minnesota at Duluth, 10 University Drive, Duluth, MN 55812, United States; Department of Marine Biogeochemistry and Toxicology, Royal Netherlands Institute for Sea Research, P.O. Box 59, NL-1790 AB Den Burg, Netherlands; Faculty of Geosciences, Utrecht University, Utrecht, Netherlands","Powers, L.A., Large Lakes Observatory, University of Minnesota at Duluth, 10 University Drive, Duluth, MN 55812, United States; Johnson, T.C., Large Lakes Observatory, University of Minnesota at Duluth, 10 University Drive, Duluth, MN 55812, United States; Werne, J.P., Large Lakes Observatory, University of Minnesota at Duluth, 10 University Drive, Duluth, MN 55812, United States; Castañeda, I.S., Large Lakes Observatory, University of Minnesota at Duluth, 10 University Drive, Duluth, MN 55812, United States; Hopmans, E.C., Department of Marine Biogeochemistry and Toxicology, Royal Netherlands Institute for Sea Research, P.O. Box 59, NL-1790 AB Den Burg, Netherlands; Sinninghe Damsté, J.S., Department of Marine Biogeochemistry and Toxicology, Royal Netherlands Institute for Sea Research, P.O. Box 59, NL-1790 AB Den Burg, Netherlands, Faculty of Geosciences, Utrecht University, Utrecht, Netherlands; Schouten, S., Department of Marine Biogeochemistry and Toxicology, Royal Netherlands Institute for Sea Research, P.O. Box 59, NL-1790 AB Den Burg, Netherlands","The role of the tropics in global climate change is actively debated, particularly in regard to the timing and magnitude of thermal and hydrological response. Continuous, high-resolution temperature records through the Last Glacial Maximum (LGM) from tropical oceans have provided much insight but surface temperature reconstructions do not exist from tropical continental environments. Here we used the TEX86 paleotemperature proxy to reconstruct mean annual lake surface temperatures through the Last Glacial Maximum (LGM) in Lake Malawi, East Africa (9°-14°S). We find a ∼3.5°C overall warming since the LGM, with temperature reversals of ∼2°C during the Younger Dryas (12.5 ka BP) and at 8.2 ka BP. Maximum Holocene temperatures of ∼29°C were found at 5 ka BP, a period preceding severe drought in Africa. These results suggest a substantial thermal response of southeastern tropical Africa to deglaciation and to varying conditions during the Holocene. Copyright 2005 by the American Geophysical Union.",,"Atmospheric temperature; Drought; Environmental impact; Glaciers; Hydrology; Tropics; Deglaciation; Global climate change; Last glacial maximum (LGM); Paleotemperature proxy; Climate change; Last Glacial Maximum; paleotemperature; tropical region; Africa; Eastern Hemisphere; Southern Africa; Sub-Saharan Africa; World",,,,,,"Alley, R.B., GISP2 ice core temperature and accumulation data (2004) IGBP PAGES/World Data Center for Paleoclimatology, , Data Contrib. Ser. 2004-2013, NOAA/NGDC Paleoclimatol. Program, Boulder, Colo; Barber, D.C., Forcing of the cold event of 8,200 years ago by catastrophic drainage of Laurentide lakes (1999) Nature, 400, pp. 344-348; Barker, P., Gasse, F., New evidence for a reduced water balance in East Africa during the Last Glacial Maximum: Implication for model-data comparison (2003) Quat. Sci. Rev., 22, pp. 823-837; Berger, A.L., Long-term variations of daily insolation and Quaternary climatic changes (1978) J. Atmos. Sci., 35, pp. 2362-2367; Blunier, T., Brook, E.J., Synchronization of the Byrd and Greenland (GISP2/GRIP) Records (2001) IGBP PAGES/World Data Center-A for Paleoclimatology, pp. 2001-2003. , Data Contrib. Ser. NOAA/NGDC Paleoclimatol. P